        <!-- ─────────────────────────────────
             04 · SYSTEM
        ───────────────────────────────── -->
        <section id="system" class="s-chapter" aria-labelledby="system-head">
          <header class="s-chapter-head">
            <span class="s-chapter-num">04</span>
            <h2 id="system-head" class="s-chapter-title">System</h2>
            <p class="s-chapter-deck">The operating contracts. Accessibility, responsive, motion.</p>
          </header>

          <!-- ACCESSIBILITY -->
          <article class="s-section" id="system-a11y">
            <header class="s-section-head">
              <span class="s-section-num">4.1</span>
              <h3>Accessibility standards</h3>
            </header>
            <p>The aesthetic is uncompromising. Accessibility is also uncompromising. These do not conflict. A system that cannot be read, navigated, or understood by all users is not disciplined — it is negligent. Baseline: WCAG 2.2 AA.</p>
            <dl class="s-contract">
              <dt>Contrast</dt>
              <dd>All body text meets 4.5:1 minimum. <code>--body-color</code> at 0.82 opacity passes in both modes. <code>--body-muted</code> (0.52) is metadata-only and never carries essential content. <code>--body-faint</code> (0.18) and <code>--body-tint</code> (0.04) are decorative — never carry meaning alone.</dd>
              <dt>Minimum type sizes</dt>
              <dd>Body: 16px. Mono metadata: 11px. No text smaller than 11px on any surface. Carousel body: 24px. Carousel mono: 10px at 1080 canvas.</dd>
              <dt>Focus states</dt>
              <dd>All interactives show a 2px solid <code>var(--accent)</code> outline on <code>:focus-visible</code> with 2px offset. Never removed. Never replaced with color-only indication. Tab order follows visual reading order.</dd>
              <dt>Touch targets</dt>
              <dd>Minimum 44×44px for all interactives. Mode toggle, nav links, plate cards, share-bar items, tags. Padding counts.</dd>
              <dt>Reduced motion</dt>
              <dd>All transitions respect <code>prefers-reduced-motion: reduce</code>. When active: no hover transforms, no progress-bar animation, no plate scale transitions. Static fallbacks only. The brand does not depend on motion for meaning.</dd>
              <dt>Color independence</dt>
              <dd>Accent red never carries meaning alone. Every red element is also distinguished by position, border, weight, or label. A monochrome printout of any page must remain fully legible.</dd>
              <dt>Keyboard navigation</dt>
              <dd>Every interactive element reachable via Tab. Visible focus on every tab stop. No focus traps. Skip-to-content link on every page. Component-scoped bindings (Escape to collapse, arrow keys for roving focus) live with the components that need them.</dd>
            </dl>
          </article>

          <!-- RESPONSIVE -->
          <article class="s-section" id="system-responsive">
            <header class="s-section-head">
              <span class="s-section-num">4.2</span>
              <h3>Responsive behavior</h3>
            </header>
            <p>The system does not have a "mobile version." It has one design that compresses. Components shed secondary elements at narrower widths but never change personality. The grid tightens. The borders remain.</p>
            <dl class="s-contract">
              <dt>Breakpoints</dt>
              <dd><strong>≤ 768px:</strong> plates stack single-column, rulers hide, outer padding drops to 18px. Grid stays. <strong>≤ 480px:</strong> display type hits its <code>clamp()</code> floor, meta rail wraps, share bar stacks, section indicator hides.</dd>
              <dt>Article frame</dt>
              <dd>Max-width 680px at every breakpoint. Padding adjusts 28px → 16px. Pull quotes, callouts, scripture blocks remain full-width within the frame. No component is ever hidden on mobile.</dd>
              <dt>Headlines</dt>
              <dd>All display type uses <code>clamp()</code> with a floor + vw preferred + ceiling. Example: <code>clamp(2.2rem, 6vw, 4.5rem)</code>. Never truncated with ellipsis. Never below the clamp floor.</dd>
              <dt>Line length</dt>
              <dd>Body copy: 55–75 characters per line (optimal 65). Enforced by the 680px frame. On mobile: compresses naturally but never below 40 characters at 16px body.</dd>
              <dt>Mobile rhythm</dt>
              <dd>Vertical spacing compresses but maintains proportion. Section margins 48 → 32px. Component padding 24 → 16px. Grid gap stays at 12px. Border weights never change. Rhythm slows slightly on mobile — more breathing room, not less.</dd>
              <dt>Horizontal overflow</dt>
              <dd><code>overflow-x: clip</code> on <code>html</code> (iOS Safari requires it on the root). <code>.page-shell</code> uses <code>clip</code> as defense-in-depth. <code>clip</code> instead of <code>hidden</code> so sticky masthead keeps working.</dd>
            </dl>
          </article>

          <!-- MOTION -->
          <article class="s-section" id="system-motion">
            <header class="s-section-head">
              <span class="s-section-num">4.3</span>
              <h3>Motion &amp; interaction states</h3>
            </header>
            <p>Motion is mechanical, not expressive. Every transition is short, linear or ease-out, and serves one purpose: confirm that an interaction registered. The brand does not bounce, spring, wobble, or delight. It responds.</p>
            <dl class="s-contract">
              <dt>Transition tokens</dt>
              <dd><code>--motion-fast</code> (120ms) for hover chrome + progress fills. <code>--motion-med</code> (180ms) for mode flip + small-chrome opacity. <code>--motion-slow</code> (300ms) for ambient reveals. <code>--ease-default</code> (<code>cubic-bezier(.2, .8, .2, 1)</code>) is the one curve. <strong>If a duration isn't in this scale, it doesn't belong in the product.</strong> Never ease-in-out. Never overshoot curves. Never transitions longer than <code>--motion-slow</code>.</dd>
              <dt>Hover states</dt>
              <dd>Plates: border-color shifts to <code>var(--accent)</code>, <code>scale(1.005)</code>. Links: border-bottom appears, color unchanged. Tags/meta: background to <code>var(--body-tint)</code>. Buttons: fg/bg invert.</dd>
              <dt>Active / pressed</dt>
              <dd>Scale to 0.98 on interactives. Immediate — no transition on press, only on release. Color does not change on active. The press is the only feedback.</dd>
              <dt>Disabled / empty</dt>
              <dd>Disabled: 0.32 opacity, <code>cursor: not-allowed</code>, no hover. Empty states: centered mono caps, <code>var(--body-muted)</code>. Never illustrated. Never friendly. Example: "Nothing here yet."</dd>
              <dt>Loading / progress</dt>
              <dd>Reading progress bar: <code>var(--ink)</code> fill, 3px height, linear left-to-right. Red was pulled from the progress bar because a red strip at viewport top competed with the masthead and diluted the accent's semantic weight. Red stays reserved for section heads, callouts, underlines, focus. Never ambient chrome.</dd>
              <dt>Error / alert</dt>
              <dd>Errors inherit the accent — the system already reserves red for emphasis. Error text: mono, uppercase, <code>var(--accent)</code>. Error borders: 2px solid <code>var(--accent)</code> on the affected field. No icons. No exclamation marks. "Required." or "Invalid format." — that register.</dd>
              <dt>Visited</dt>
              <dd>Visited article links on homepage plates: no color change. The system does not differentiate read from unread. If tracking is needed, it happens in metadata ("Read" tag), not in link styling.</dd>
            </dl>
          </article>
        </section>

        <!-- ─────────────────────────────────
             05 · SOCIAL
        ───────────────────────────────── -->
        <section id="social" class="s-chapter" aria-labelledby="social-head">
          <header class="s-chapter-head">
            <span class="s-chapter-num">05</span>
            <h2 id="social-head" class="s-chapter-title">Social</h2>
            <p class="s-chapter-deck">The social template system. Four canvases, two modes, one doctrine. Every slide is a stripped-down article panel.</p>
          </header>

          <!-- SOCIAL CAROUSELS -->
          <article class="s-section" id="social-carousels">
            <header class="s-section-head">
              <span class="s-section-num">5.1</span>
              <h3>Social carousels</h3>
            </header>
            <p>Every social artifact is a stripped-down version of the article page — same grid, same panel border, same monospace eyebrow, same display type. Each template ships in four canonical formats (portrait, story, square, landscape) and two modes (dark, light). Modes may vary <em>between</em> posts in a campaign (e.g., announcement in light, carousel in dark) but never <em>within</em> a single carousel. If a slide could not be a printed broadsheet panel, it is wrong.</p>
            <p class="s-note"><strong>Pattern library.</strong> The full 232-artboard system lives at <code>imjustdex-social-templates.html</code> in the brand-voice repo — 29 filterable buckets, every one shipping all four formats in dark and light. Each bucket is a template (blog announcement, carousel S1–S10, devotional, letter, quote card, music drop, dispatch, field note, essay teaser, now card, reckoning, reader Q&amp;A, speaking/show, cultural reply, recipe, liner notes) plus two modifier extensions (<code>.field.memoir</code>, <code>.reckoning.exegesis</code>) and two primitive affordances (<code>.cycle-marker</code>, <code>.fn-mark</code> + <code>.footnotes</code>).</p>

            <dl class="s-contract">
              <dt>Grid</dt>
              <dd>46px repeating background lines at <code>rgba(255,255,255,.16)</code> dark, <code>rgba(0,0,0,.14)</code> light. Identical across all surfaces — site, carousels, decks, print. Non-negotiable.</dd>
              <dt>Panel border</dt>
              <dd>Every slide ships the brand-block outline. 3px content borders for frames, 2px chrome borders for inner treatments — same doctrine as the web.</dd>
              <dt>Type</dt>
              <dd>Anton for display, IBM Plex Sans for argument, mono for metadata. Binary weight scale (400 / 700) — same as the site. <code>font-synthesis: none</code> site-wide so Anton can't be faux-bolded.</dd>
              <dt>Red doctrine</dt>
              <dd><code>#c00</code> identical across both modes for borders, fills, and display text ≥ 18px. <code>--sig-text</code> flips to <code>#ff4d4d</code> (7.54:1 on #060606) for small red text on dark. Same rule as the web.</dd>
              <dt>Scripture</dt>
              <dd>Exact KJV only — never paraphrased. Enforced by <code>npm run lint</code> against <code>kjv-verses.json</code>.</dd>
              <dt>Pagination</dt>
              <dd>Dots pagination for carousels ≤5 slides. Count rail (<code>01 · 05</code>) for carousels &gt;5.</dd>
            </dl>
          </article>

          <!-- PLATFORM DIMENSIONS -->
          <article class="s-section" id="social-platforms">
            <header class="s-section-head">
              <span class="s-section-num">5.2</span>
              <h3>Platform dimensions</h3>
            </header>
            <p>Every social template ships in four canonical formats. One campaign file, four dimensional variants, plus opt-in safe-zone modifiers for per-platform UI chrome. All inherit Refined Brutalism — grid, panel border, mono metadata, display headlines. Upload the matching format per destination.</p>

            <div class="s-platform-grid">
              <div class="s-platform-card">
                <h4>Portrait · 1080 × 1440</h4>
                <dl>
                  <div><dt>Aspect</dt><dd>3 : 4</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Instagram feed</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>IG profile grid</dt><dd>survives 3:4 crop</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Pinterest</dt><dd>accepted</dd></div>
                </dl>
              </div>

              <div class="s-platform-card">
                <h4>Story · 1080 × 1920</h4>
                <dl>
                  <div><dt>Aspect</dt><dd>9 : 16</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Instagram Stories</dt><dd>default 250 / 250</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Facebook Stories</dt><dd><code>.fb-stories</code> 270 / 380</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Instagram Reels</dt><dd><code>.reels</code> 210 / 440 / 90</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>TikTok</dt><dd><code>.tiktok</code> 140 / 324 / 164</dd></div>
                </dl>
              </div>

              <div class="s-platform-card">
                <h4>Square · 1080 × 1080</h4>
                <dl>
                  <div><dt>Aspect</dt><dd>1 : 1</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Threads</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>X / Twitter</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Facebook feed</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>LinkedIn feed</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>IG grid crop</dt><dd><code>.ig-grid-safe</code> 135 / 135</dd></div>
                </dl>
              </div>

              <div class="s-platform-card">
                <h4>Landscape · 1200 × 630</h4>
                <dl>
                  <div><dt>Aspect</dt><dd>1.91 : 1</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>OG meta image</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>X link card</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>LinkedIn preview</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Facebook link</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Mobile crop</dt><dd><code>.og-safe</code> horiz +120</dd></div>
                  <div><dt>Blog hero</dt><dd>native</dd></div>
                </dl>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="s-note"><strong>Out of scope.</strong> Facebook Reels (needs ~670px bottom, not currently a variant), YouTube video thumbnails (1280×720 landscape-adjacent), LinkedIn 1584×396 profile banner, full-bleed TikTok video-thumbnail frames. Add as new dimensional classes or modifiers when a distribution channel commits — never in advance.</p>
          </article>
        </section>

